      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here is the paper you're looking for:\n\n## **arXiv 2505.15784: \"Large Language Models as Computable Approximations to Solomonoff Induction\"**\n\n**Link:** [https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.15784](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.15784)\n\n**Published:** May 21, 2025\n\n### Summary\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The paper addresses the rapid advancement of large language models (LLMs) and notes that existing theoretical frameworks remain fragmented in explaining emergent phenomena through a unified mathematical lens."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\nThe authors establish a formal connection between LLM architectures and Algorithmic Information Theory (AIT) by proving two key results: "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "(1) the training process computationally approximates the Solomonoff prior through loss minimization interpreted as program length optimization, and (2) next-token prediction implements approximate Solomonoff induction."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "They leverage AIT to provide a unified theoretical explanation for in-context learning, few-shot learning, and scaling laws."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Furthermore, their theoretical insights lead to a principled method for few-shot example selection that prioritizes samples where models exhibit lower predictive confidence."
      }
